'''Pregnancy-associated malaria''' ('''PAM''') or '''placental malaria''' is a presentation of the common illness that is particularly life threatening to both mother and developing [[fetus]].<ref name="CNRS">{{cite journal |last1=Srivastava |first1=Anand |last2=Gangnard |first2=Stéphane |last3=Round |first3=Adam |last4=Dechavanne |first4=Sébastien |last5=Juillerat |first5=Alexandre |last6=Raynal |first6=Bertrand |last7=Faure |first7=Grazyna |last8=Baron |first8=Bruno |last9=Ramboarina |first9=Stéphanie |title=Full-length extracellular region of the var2CSA variant of PfEMP1 is required for specific, high-affinity binding to CSA |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=107 |issue=11 |pages=4884–9 |year=2010 |pmid=20194779 |pmc=2841952 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1000951107 |laysummary=http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/03/100309112025.htm |laysource=ScienceDaily |laydate=March 12, 2010}}</ref> PAM is caused primarily by infection with ''[[Plasmodium falciparum]]'',<ref name="CNRS"/><ref>{{cite web|title=CDC-Malaria-Malaria Parasites |url=http://www.cdc.gov/malaria/about/biology/parasites.html |publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention}}</ref> the most dangerous of the four species of malaria-causing parasites that infect humans.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Perlmann |first1=P |last2=Troye-Blomberg |first2=M |title=Malaria blood-stage infection and its control by the immune system |journal=Folia biologica |volume=46 |issue=6 |pages=210–8 |year=2000 |pmid=11140853}}</ref> During her first [[pregnancy]], a woman faces a much higher risk of contracting [[malaria]] and of associated complications.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lives at Risk: Malaria in Pregnancy |url=http://who.int/features/2003/04b/en/ |publisher=WHO |accessdate=March 30, 2011}}</ref> Prevention and treatment of malaria are essential components of [[prenatal care]] in areas where the parasite is endemic.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Duffy|first=P. E.|coauthors=M. Fried|title=Malaria in the Pregnant Woman|journal=Current Topics in Microbiology and Immunology|year=2005|volume=295|pages=169–200}}</ref>

While the average adult citizen of an endemic region possesses some [[Immunity (medical)|immunity]] to the parasite,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Doolan |first1=Denise L. |last2=Dobano |first2=Carlota |last3=Baird |first3=J. Kevin |title=Acquired Immunity to Malaria |journal=Clinical Microbiology Reviews |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=13–36, Table of Contents |year=2009 |pmid=19136431 |pmc=2620631 |doi=10.1128/CMR.00025-08}}</ref> pregnancy causes complications that leave the woman and fetus extremely vulnerable.<ref name="CNRS"/> The parasite interferes with transmission of vital substances through the fetal [[placenta]],<ref name="CNRS"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Matteelli |first1=BY |last2=Caligaris |first2=S |last3=Castelli |first3=F |last4=Carosi |first4=G |title=The placenta and malaria |journal=Annals of Tropical Medicine and Parasitology |volume=91 |issue=7 |pages=803–10 |year=1997 |pmid=9625937 |doi=10.1080/00034989760563}}</ref> often resulting in [[stillbirth]], [[spontaneous abortion]], or dangerously low birth weight.<ref name="CNRS"/> The tragedy of malaria in developing countries receives abundant attention from the international health community, but until recently PAM and its unique complications were not adequately addressed.<ref name=RBM>{{cite web|title=Roll Back Malaria: Malaria in Pregnancy|url=http://www.rollbackmalaria.org/cmc_upload/0/000/015/369/RBMInfosheet_4.htm|publisher=WHO|accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>

==Signs and Symptoms==
Women experiencing PAM may exhibit normal symptoms of malaria, but may also be asymptomatic or present with more mild symptoms, including a lack of the characteristic fever. This may prevent a woman from seeking treatment despite the danger to herself and her unborn child.<ref name=Desai>{{cite journal|last=Desai|first=Meghna|coauthors=et al.|title=Epidemiology and burden of malaria in pregnancy|journal=The Lancet|date=22|year=2007|month=January|volume=7|issue=2|pages=93–104|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science?_ob=ArticleURL&_udi=B6W8X-4MWB62F-P&_user=655954&_coverDate=02%2F28%2F2007&_rdoc=1&_fmt=high&_orig=gateway&_origin=gateway&_sort=d&_docanchor=&view=c&_acct=C000035538&_version=1&_urlVersion=0&_userid=655954&md5=57b59fa469edb157b1d3e00e19e79a6b&searchtype=a|accessdate=April 14, 2011|doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(07)70021-X}}</ref><ref name=CDCLA>{{cite web|title=Burden of Malaria in Pregnancy in Latin America Not Known|url=http://www.cdc.gov/malaria/malaria_worldwide/cdc_activities/activreg.html|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref>

==Cause==
The disease results from the aggregation of [[erythrocytes]] infected by ''[[Plasmodium falciparum]]'' which have been shown to adhere to chondroitin sulfate A (CSA) on placental [[proteoglycans]] causing them to accumulate in the [[intervillous space]]s of the placenta, blocking the crucial flow of nutrients from mother to embryo.<ref name="CNRS"/>

== Epidemiology ==
Globally, an estimated 125 million or more pregnant women per year risk contracting PAM.<ref name=125mil>{{cite web|title=New study finds 125 million pregnancies globally at risk from malaria every year|url=http://www.mip-consortium.org/resource_centre/press_releases/newstudyfinds125million.htm|publisher=Malaria in Pregnancy Consortium|accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref> Pregnancy-related malaria causes around 100,000 infant deaths each year, due in large part to low birth weight.<ref name=Desai />

